# Plain-language summary

**Companion to:** *[Paper title]* ([version/status]).

**Reading status:** This is an explanatory companion to the paper. It is not
the canonical published artifact, does not silently amend the version of
record, and introduces no new paper claims.

[Write two to four natural, README-style paragraphs for an experienced software
engineer or systems researcher. State the practical or conceptual question,
why it matters, and the capability, distinction, or result the paper adds.
Translate rather than compress: do not inventory sections, open with notation,
or replace the argument with an analogy. Explain unavoidable terms once and
preserve the paper's actual level of confidence—a hypothesis, model,
architecture, theorem, specimen, simulation, and empirical result are not
interchangeable. The reader should finish knowing whether this is a paper they
need to read.]

## Claim boundary

[In one compact note, state the strongest material nonclaim, any current
editorial qualification, and the boundary between formal, empirical,
architectural, and runtime warrant. Do not let this note become the organizing
structure of the overview. Do not use later formal work to retroactively
certify the paper without an exact reviewed crosswalk.]

